    {
      "turn_number": 32,
      "role": "persona",
      "type": "response",
      "text": "Yeah — thank you for asking. One thing we didn’t really talk about is how small things made a big difference: a midwife who sat down and actually listened, the nurse who dimmed the lights when I asked. Those moments reminded me I wasn’t just a “low-risk chart.” But what I really wish people knew is how past hurt follows you into the delivery room. I wanted staff to ask about that, not just my blood pressure — to offer trauma-informed care, not assumptions.\n\nI also wish there was more practical help for someone my age — help finding steady work, affordable childcare, and home visits after birth. Mental health support needs to be real and easy to get, not a pamphlet shoved in a discharge folder. And please stop acting like young, single parents are less capable; respect matters.\n\nOverall I’m grateful in parts, scared in others, hopeful for my baby. My biggest hope is that future care treats people as whole people — with histories, fears, and strengths — not just prenatal numbers.",
      "responding_to_question_id": null,
      "input_tokens": 1356,
      "output_tokens": 472
    }
